  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. Specific legal definitions vary between jurisdictions, but typically include:\n\n1. Key elements common to most legal definitions:\n- Attempting to disguise the source of illegal funds\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly \"clean\" money\n- Conducting financial transactions to hide criminal proceeds\n\n2. Common legal categories of money laundering:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial systems)\n- Layering (creating complex financial transactions)\n- Integration (making funds appear legitimate)\n\n3. Typical legal standards for prosecution:\n- Intentional concealment of funds' criminal origins\n- Knowledge that money derives from illegal activities\n- Purposeful attempt to disguise financial transactions\n\n4. Jurisdictional variations exist, but most definitions involve:\n- Criminal intent\n- Financial transactions\n- Proceeds from specific predicate crimes\n\n5. International standards often set by:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- United Nations conventions\n- Individual national legislation\n\nSpecific legal details can vary significantly between countries and legal systems.",
